Simulation for BostonData2.csv

Data Preparation

The dataset BostonData2.csv contains first 14 columns transformed from Boston Housing data with Y being the response variable. 78 extra predictors are added, which are the quadratic terms of the 12 numerical predictors (excluding the binary predictor chas) and all pairwise interactions between the 12 numerical predictors.

bostonData2 = read.csv("BostonData2.csv")
head(bostonData2)

We remove column X, as it is an index column.

bostonData2 = bostonData2[, -1]

Some algorithms need the matrix/vector input (instead of a data frame)

X = data.matrix(bostonData2[,-1])  
Y = bostonData2[,1]

Seven Procedures

Run the seven procedures and save the results in MSPE. We randomly split the data into two parts, 75% for training and 25% for testing.

n = length(Y)
ntest = round(n * 0.25)  # test set size
test.id = sample(1:n, ntest)

MSPE = rep(0, 7)
names(MSPE) = c("Full", "R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR")

Full Model

full_model = function(data_train, data_test) {
  full.model = lm(Y ~ ., data = data_train)
  Ytest.pred = predict(full.model, newdata = data_test)
  mean((data_test$Y - Ytest.pred)^2)
}

MSPE[1] = full_model(data_train = bostonData2[-test.id,], data_test=bostonData2[test.id,])

Ridge

Ridge with lambda.min and lambda.1se. With my experiments, the lambda of the minimum MSE is not falling at the boundary with the lambda sequence myridge.lambda.seq1. So through out the experiments for BostonData2.csv, I will stick to myridge.lambda.seq1 for my ridge regression model.

myridge.lambda.seq1 = exp(seq(-10, -2, length.out = 100))

my_ridge = function(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, lambda.seq) {
  # stick to the same lambda sequence for the rest of experiments.
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, alpha = 0, lambda = lambda.seq)
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = cv.out$lambda.min, newx = X_test)
  MSPE.min = mean((y_test - Ytest.pred)^2)

  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = cv.out$lambda.1se, newx = X_test)
  MSPE.1se = mean((y_test - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  list(MSPE.min = MSPE.min, MSPE.1se = MSPE.1se)
}

MSPEs_ridge = my_ridge(
  X_train = X[-test.id, ], y_train = Y[-test.id], 
  X_test = X[test.id, ], y_test = Y[test.id],
  lambda.seq = myridge.lambda.seq1)
(MSPE[2] = MSPEs_ridge$MSPE.min)
## [1] 0.02594114
(MSPE[3] = MSPEs_ridge$MSPE.1se)

In your submission, choose your lambda sequence based on one or two traing-and-test splits, and then stick to that sequence for all 50 iterations.

Lasso

The CV plot indicates that the default lambda sequence for Lasso seems fine. I will stick to the default lambda sequence through out the experiments.

cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 1)

Lasso with lambda.min, lambda.1se, and Refit

my_lasso = function(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test) {
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, alpha = 1)
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = cv.out$lambda.min, newx = X_test)
  MSPE.min = mean((y_test - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = cv.out$lambda.1se, newx = X_test)
  MSPE.1se = mean((y_test - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  mylasso.coef = predict(cv.out, s = cv.out$lambda.1se, type = "coefficients")
  var.sel = row.names(mylasso.coef)[which(mylasso.coef != 0)[-1]]
  train_data = as.data.frame(cbind(Y=y_train, X_train[, c(var.sel)]))
  mylasso.refit = lm(Y ~ ., train_data)
  Ytest.pred = predict(mylasso.refit, newdata = as.data.frame(X_test))
  MSPE.refit = mean((Ytest.pred - y_test)^2)
  list(MSPE.min = MSPE.min, MSPE.1se = MSPE.1se, MSPE.refit = MSPE.refit)
}

MSPEs_lasso = my_lasso(
  X_train = X[-test.id, ], y_train = Y[-test.id], 
  X_test = X[test.id, ], y_test = Y[test.id]
)
(MSPE[4] = MSPEs_lasso$MSPE.min)

PCR

The principle components regression command, pcr, returns both the CV errors and the adjusted CV errors. For the definition of adjusted CV used in pcr, check Sec 2.4 of this paper.

pcr_fit = pcr(Y ~ ., data= bostonData2[-test.id, ], validation="CV")
CVerr = RMSEP(pcr_fit)$val[1, , ]
best.ncomp = which.min(CVerr) - 1 
best.ncomp
## 58 comps 
##       58
my_pcr = function(data_train, data_test) {
  pcr_fit = pcr(Y ~ ., data= data_train, validation="CV")
  CVerr = RMSEP(pcr_fit)$val[1, , ]
  adjCVerr = RMSEP(pcr_fit)$val[2, , ]
  best.ncomp = which.min(CVerr) - 1 
  
  if (best.ncomp==0) {
    Ytest.pred = mean(data_train$Y)
  } else {
    Ytest.pred = predict(pcr_fit, data_test, ncomp=best.ncomp)
  }
  mean((Ytest.pred - data_test$Y)^2)
}

MSPE[7] = my_pcr(data_train = bostonData2[-test.id, ], data_test = bostonData2[test.id,])

Note that we have to subtract one from which.min(CVerr) since the 1st column of the CV table corresponds to the CV error with zero components (i.e., the model with just the intercept) and the k-th column of the CV table corresponds to (k-1) components.

The prediction function does not seem to work when best.ncomp = 0. So we have to handle that case separately.

Simulation

The function one_sim is defined to run a single simulation and the utility method run_sims is defined to run multiple simulations. The simulation result of both methods are returned in the form of R data.frame. In each simulation, we randomly split the data into two parts, 75% for training and 25% for testing.

one_sim = function(data_train, data_test, ridge.lambda.seq, full_model_enabled) {
  X_train = data.matrix(data_train[,-1])
  y_train = data_train[,1]
  X_test = data.matrix(data_test[,-1])
  y_test = data_test[,1]
  
  if (full_model_enabled) {
    MSPE.full = full_model(data_train = data_train, data_test = data_test)
  }
  
  MSPEs_ridge = my_ridge(
    X_train = X_train, y_train = y_train, 
    X_test = X_test, y_test = y_test,
    lambda.seq = ridge.lambda.seq)
  MSPE.ridge.min = MSPEs_ridge$MSPE.min
  MSPE.ridge.1se = MSPEs_ridge$MSPE.1se
  
  MSPEs_lasso = my_lasso(
    X_train = X_train, y_train = y_train, 
    X_test = X_test, y_test = y_test)
  MSPE.lasso.min = MSPEs_lasso$MSPE.min
  MSPE.lasso.1se = MSPEs_lasso$MSPE.1se
  MSPE.l.refit = MSPEs_lasso$MSPE.refit
  
  MSPE.pcr = my_pcr(data_train = data_train, data_test = data_test)
  result = data.frame(
    Model = c("R_min",        "R_1se",        "L_min",       "L_1se",         "L_Refit",    "PCR"),
    MSPE =  c(MSPE.ridge.min, MSPE.ridge.1se, MSPE.lasso.min, MSPE.lasso.1se, MSPE.l.refit, MSPE.pcr),
    stringsAsFactors = TRUE
  )
  if (full_model_enabled) {
    rbind(
      data.frame(Model = c("Full"), MSPE = MSPE.full, stringsAsFactors = TRUE),
      result)
  } else {
    result
  }
}

run_sims = function(data, runs, ridge.lambda.seq, full_model_enabled) {
  run_sim = function() {
    # data = bostonData2
    # full_model_enabled = TRUE
    n = dim(data)[1]
    ntest = round(n * 0.25)
    test.id = sample(1:n, ntest)
    one_sim(
      data_train = data[-test.id, ], 
      data_test = data[test.id, ], 
      ridge.lambda.seq = ridge.lambda.seq,
      full_model_enabled = full_model_enabled)
  }
  
  # data = bostonData2
  # runs=3
  # full_model_enabled = TRUE
  result = replicate(n = runs, expr = run_sim(), simplify = FALSE)
  combined_result = do.call(rbind, result)
  colnames(combined_result) = c("Model", "MSPE")
  combined_result
}

We will repeat the following simulation 50 times.

result_bd2 = run_sims(
  data = bostonData2, runs = 50, 
  ridge.lambda.seq = myridge.lambda.seq1, full_model_enabled = TRUE)
head(result_bd2)
dim(result_bd2)
## [1] 350   2
result_bd2$Model = factor(
  result_bd2$Model,
  levels=c("R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR", "Full"))
boxplot(MSPE ~ Model, data = as.data.frame(result_bd2), col = rainbow(7), xlab="")

R_min stands for Ridge with lambda.min model and R_1se is for Ridge with lambda.1se model. L_min, L_1se and L_Refit stand for Lasso with lambda.min model, Lasso with lambda.1se and the refit linear addictive model with coefficients from L_1se model respectively. PCR is for principal component regression model.

From the plot, we can see that Lasso L_min model performs slightly better than Lasso L_1se. This is normally the case, as L_1se is the simpler model chosen in one standard deviation of CV error. Similarly, Ridge R_min model performs slightly better than Ridge R_1se model. The refit linear addictive model L_1se performs slightly better than Lasso L_1se, which is normally the case as refit model will utilize the full capacity of predictors. PCR model has similar performance as Lasso L_min and Ridge R_min models. As the dataset does not contain much noise, the top k principal components PCR picked capture the signal well. The full model Full also perform fine in the given dataset.

Simulation for BostonData3.csv

Data Preparation

In BostonData3.csv dataset, the first 92 columns are the same as BostonData2.csv, and the remaining 500 columns are artificially generated noise features.

bostonData3 = read.csv("BostonData3.csv")
head(bostonData3)

We remove column X, as it contains index. Also, we can see that the number of predictor p is bigger than sample size. Therefore, we will not fit a full linear model in BostonData3.csv simulation.

bostonData3 = bostonData3[,-1]
dim(bostonData3)
## [1] 506 592

Some algorithms need the matrix/vector input (instead of a data frame)

X2 = data.matrix(bostonData3[,-1])  
Y2 = bostonData3[,1]

Lambdas for Ridge and Lasso

Ridge

Ridge with lambda.min and lambda.1se. With my experiments, the lambda of the minimum MSE is not falling at the boundary with the lambda sequence myridge.lambda.seq2. So through out the experiments for BostonData3.csv, I will stick to myridge.lambda.seq2 for my ridge regression model.

myridge.lambda.seq2 = exp(seq(-4, 5, length.out = 100))
cv.out = cv.glmnet(X2[-test.id, ], Y2[-test.id], alpha = 0, 
                   lambda = myridge.lambda.seq2)
plot(cv.out)

which.min(cv.out$lambda > cv.out$lambda.min) == length(cv.out$lambda)
## [1] FALSE

Lasso

The CV plot indicates that the default lambda sequence for Lasso seems fine. I will stick to the default lambda sequence through out the experiments for BostonData3.csv.

cv.out = cv.glmnet(X2[-test.id, ], Y2[-test.id], alpha = 1)
plot(cv.out)

Simulation

We will repeat the following simulation 50 times.

result_bd3 = run_sims(
  data = bostonData3, runs=50, 
  ridge.lambda.seq = myridge.lambda.seq2, full_model_enabled = FALSE)
head(result_bd3)
dim(result_bd3)
## [1] 300   2
result_bd3$Model = factor(
  result_bd3$Model,
  levels=c("R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR"))
boxplot(MSPE ~ Model, data = as.data.frame(result_bd3), col = rainbow(7), xlab="")

R_min stands for Ridge with lambda.min model and R_1se is for Ridge with lambda.1se model. L_min, L_1se and L_Refit stand for Lasso with lambda.min model, Lasso with lambda.1se and the refit linear addictive model with coefficients from L_1se model respectively. PCR is for principal component regression model.

From the plot, we can see that Lasso L_min, Lasso L_1se, and the refit linear addictive model L_Refit models performs better than other models. This is expected, as we add lots of noisy predictors into the dataset and Lasso models can eliminate noises(but it may also eliminate week signal predictors). The refit linear model L_Refit is doing better than Lasso L_1se, which is normally the case as refit model will utilize the full capacity of predictors while Lasso L_1se may suppress some week signals. Ridge R_min and Ridge R_1se don’t perform well in this case. This is because Ridge models don’t eliminate noises and they only shrink these noises more than signal predictors. As the dataset contains lots of noisy predictors, Ridge models contain too many small coefficients fitted to noisy predictors. As a result, Ridge models R_min and R_1se don’t perform well in this case. PCR model perform the worst in this case. This is expected as for each principal component, it is a linear combinations of all predictors. When the dataset contains a lot of noise predictors, these noisy information will be included in the top k principal components through linear combinations. This explains the bad performance of PCR model with BostonData3.csv dataset.

Comparing the plots on the two datasets

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
result_bd2_no_full = as.data.frame(result_bd2[result_bd2$Model!="Full",])
result_bd2_no_full = droplevels(result_bd2_no_full)
boxplot(MSPE ~ Model, data = result_bd2_no_full, 
        col = rainbow(7), xlab="", main="BostonData2.csv",
        ylim=c(0.01, 0.10))
boxplot(MSPE ~ Model, data = as.data.frame(result_bd3), 
        col = rainbow(7), xlab="", ylab="", main="BostonData3.csv",
        ylim=c(0.01, 0.10))

Note that we don’t fit a full linear model in BostonData3.csv simulation, as we know that the number of predictor p is bigger than sample size. Therefore, we will not fit a full linear model in BostonData3.csv simulation and we don’t do comparison for full model.

R_min stands for Ridge with lambda.min model and R_1se is for Ridge with lambda.1se model. L_min, L_1se and L_Refit stand for Lasso with lambda.min model, Lasso with lambda.1se and the refit linear addictive model with coefficients from L_1se model respectively. PCR is for principal component regression model.

Overall, all models performs worse in BostonData3.csv than in BostonData2.csv. But out of them, Lasso models L_min, L_1se and the linear refit L_Refit model performs better than other models in noisy dataset BostonData3.csv. This is expected, as Lasso models can eliminate noises. However, while they are trying to eliminate noises, they may also kills week signal predictors. That is why Lasso models performs slightly worse in BostonData3.csv(MSPEs are above 0.04) than the ones in BostonData2.csv(MSPEs are around 0.03). For both dataset, the refit linear models L_Refit are doing better than Lasso L_1se, which is normally the case as refit model will utilize the full capacity of predictors while Lasso L_1se may suppress some week signals. Additionally, we can see the two Ridge models, R_min and R_1se perform much worse with noisy dataset BostonData3.csv than the ones in BostonData2.csv. This is expected, as Ridge models don’t eliminate noises but they only shrink these noises more than signal predictors. BostonData3.csv contains a large number of noisy predictors, Ridge models contain too many small coefficients fitted to these noisy predictors. As a results, they perform much worse than the ones in BostonData2.csv. Finally, PCR model performs well with BostonData2.csv, but performs the worst with noisy dataset BostonData3.csv. This is expected as each principal component is a linear combinations of all predictors. When the dataset contains a lot of noise predictors, these noisy information will be included in the top k principal components through linear combinations. Whereas, in BostonData2.csv, there is not much noise and the PCR model performs very well.
